<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-113-212  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 113 212.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  March 16 1989 n1137* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Goolies and ghosties: daemons find their place on the personaldesktop. (programs that run concurrently in background)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MS-DOSMultitaskingApplicationsMicrocomputersConcurrency Control.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>GOOLIES andamp; GHOSTIES: DAEMONS FIND THEIR PLACE ON THE PERSONAL DESKTOP Thingsthat go bump in the night may seem a world away from the computer industry,but the personal computer user may soon be leaving the more routine aspectsof data processing to the daemons, phantoms and sprites.andP;  These are the namesgiven to a new class of programs designed to perform basic and useful tasks,yet to run in background, almost undetected by the user, reports the New YorkTimes.andP;  Although widely used on mainframes and larger minicomputers, thesewere previously unavailable to smaller personal computers since CP/M andMS-DOS operating systems only allow one program to run at a time.andP;  However,with the advent of multi-tasking operating systems such as Digital Research'sConcurrent DOS, Microsoft's OS/2 and Unix, will support daemon software.andP;  Asoperating systems become more sophisticated, daemon has also evolved.andP;  Itsuses range from the detection of computer crime, to sorting through andpicking out relevent items on electronic news networks, to enabling users toaccess simple information about other users on the same computer, or network.andO;In the future, programmers predict that daemon programs will become likeintelligent assistants, quietly anticipating the requirements of the user.andO;</TEXT></DOC>